1 INTRODUCTION ¶

Titanic Competition¶

This notebook details our approach to the Titanic-Machine Learning Disaster Competition. This competition requires us to predict which passengers survived the Titanic disaster using machine learning. For more on this see the competition page.

We are provided the following:

  • Training Data: This is what we will train our model on
  • Test Data: This is what we will test our model on to determine surviveability

Our Approach¶

Things to look at

  • develop an understanding of the nature of data
  • analyse the data through histograms
  • analyse the categorical data through value counts
  • Decide whether or not to include different sets of missing data. Does the missing data provide an important aspect which should be included or should this data be excluded to prevent the skewing of the data?
  • Check the correlation between metrics
  • seek common themes -> wealth/location/gender etc
  • feature engineering
  • preprocess data together or use a transformer
  • Check the scaling of the data
  • Model Baseline
  • Model comparison with CV

3.2 Brief Analysis of data types / Data dictionary ¶

The data which must be assessed has different categories and features as described by the Titanic competition page which can be accessed at data. These categories and notable features are described below:

Variable Definition Key
survival Survival 0 = No, 1 = Yes
pclass Ticket class 1 = 1st, 2 = 2nd, 3 = 3rd
sex Sex
Age Age in years
sibsp # of siblings / spouses aboard the Titanic
parch # of parents / children aboard the Titanic
ticket Ticket number
fare Passenger fare
cabin Cabin number
embarked Port of Embarkation C = Cherbourg, Q = Queenstown, S = Southampton

A close insepction of the different types of variables:

  • pclass: A proxy for socio-economic status (SES)

    • 1st = Upper
    • 2nd = Middle
    • 3rd = Lower

  • age: Age is fractional if less than 1. If the age is estimated, is it in the form of xx.5

  • sibsp: The dataset defines family relations in this way...

    • Sibling = brother, sister, stepbrother, stepsister
    • Spouse = husband, wife (mistresses and fiancés were ignored)

  • parch: The dataset defines family relations in this way...

  • Parent = mother, father
  • Child = daughter, son, stepdaughter, stepson
    • Some children travelled only with a nanny, therefore parch=0 for them

Detecting and Removing Outliers:

This function will loop through a list of features and detect outliers in each one of those features. In each loop, a data point is deemed an outlier if it is less than the first quartile minus the outlier step or exceeds third quartile plus the outlier step. The outlier step is defined as 1.5 times the interquartile range. Once the outliers have been determined for one feature, their indices will be stored in a list before proceeding to the next feature and the process repeats until the very last feature is completed. Finally, using the list with outlier indices, we will count the frequencies of the index numbers and return them if their frequency exceeds n times.

In [21]:
def detect_outliers(df, n, features):
    
    outlier_indices = [] 
    for col in features: 
        Q1 = np.percentile(df[col], 25)
        Q3 = np.percentile(df[col], 75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        outlier_step = 1.5 * IQR 
        outlier_list_col = df[(df[col] < Q1 - outlier_step) | (df[col] > Q3 + outlier_step)].index
        outlier_indices.extend(outlier_list_col) 
    outlier_indices = Counter(outlier_indices)
    multiple_outliers = list(key for key, value in outlier_indices.items() if value > n) 
    return multiple_outliers
# Print out the possible outliers for demonstration
training.loc[detect_outliers(training, 2, ['Age', 'SibSp', 'Parch', 'Fare']), :]

Numerical Analysis Conclusion

Comparing the surival rates and correlations accross Age, SibSp, Parch and Fare numerical variables it can be found that:

  1. Age: Children and older passengers were more likely to survive
  2. Fare: Rich passengers were more likely to survive
  3. Parch: Children with parents were more likely to survive
  4. SibSp: On average passengers with smaller families were more likely to survive. However it was found that individuals with no siblings or spouses were less likely to survive than those with one or two siblings or spouse.

Categorical Variables Conclusion

Comparing the survival rates accross Survived, Sex, Pclass and Embarked it can be deduced that:

  • A passenger is more likely to not have survived than to survive
  • A passenger is more likely to survive if they were in 1st class
  • A passenger is more likely to survive if they were female
  • There is no clear link between survivablity and the location where they embarked.

5.3 Specific Feature Engineering¶

1) From SibSp and Parch determine the size of a family and how many passengers travelled alone to analyse the impact it has on the passeneger's survival rate.

2) From Cabin determine the number of cabins purchased by passengers to investiage the impact owning multiple cabins has on survival.

3) From Cabin organise the cabins by evalauting the cabin letters to examine if the location of the cabin impact the survival rate.

4) From Name determine if a person's title with grouping.

5) From Name determine if a person's title without grouping

6) From Age determine if a passenger's age impacts their survival rate by filling in the missing values using the median.

7) From Age determine if a passenger's age impacts their survival rate by filling in the missing values using the mean.

8) From Age determine if a passenger's age impacts their survival rate by creating age bins using the median the fill in the missing values.

9) From Age determine if a passenger's age impacts their survival rate by creating age bins using the mean the fill in the missing values.

10) From Fare calculate bins and analyse the effect it has on the survival rate.

11) From Fare calculate a normalised value.

6 MODEL BUILDING ¶

This section focuses on building the models used to determine survival rates. Models must be fitted to the training set and then can be applied to the test set for obtaining results. Firstly, the provided training set is split into sections for training and validation of the models ability. Overfitting is the process by which the Machine Learning algorithm effectively learns too much from the training set, and thus even includes noise in the data, this is why preprocessing is so important.

These algorithms are all supervised methods as labels are included with the data.

In [106]:
validationAccuracy = []
actualAccuracy = []

# default
y = training['Survived']

Accuracy and Error:

The accuracy for the training and validaton sets are shown for different datasets that make use of various parameters. These parameters vary consequetively with datasets affecting each model differently. Each parameter contains differing parameters that provide insight into the differing characteristics of each model.

Accuracy is obtained by comparing the model predictions with the actual data. Error is obtained using the mean square error.

6.1 Logistic Regression: ¶

A fundamental classification technique similar to linear regression and is well suited to binary classifications. This technique makes use of the natural logirithm and the sigmoid function to predict outcomes. As such, the value of the prediction function is close to 0 or 1, since it is the sigmoid function of a linear function, weighted by the estimator inputs. Learn more.

In [107]:
logreg_acc = []
Y_pred_logreg = []
validation_acc = []
training_acc = []
mse_valid = []
mse_train = []

for i in range(len(featureEngineering)):
    if type(featureEngineering[i]) != np.ndarray:
        feature = featureEngineering[i].copy(deep=True) 
        X = feature.drop(columns= ['Survived'])
        y = feature['Survived']
    test_data_log = testFeatureEngineering[i].copy(deep=True) 
    
    # validation
    X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test=train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.2,random_state=1)
    logreg = LogisticRegression()
    logreg.fit(X_train, y_train)
    Y_pred = logreg.predict(X_test)
    
    # accuracy
    print('Accuracy for fe' + str(i))
    a1 = metrics.accuracy_score(y_train, logreg.predict(X_train))
    print("Train set Accuracy: ", a1)
    a2 = metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, Y_pred)
    print("Test set Accuracy: ", a2)
    a3 = f1_score(y_test, Y_pred, average='weighted')
    print('F1 Score:', a3)
    a4 = cross_val_score(logreg,X_train,y_train,cv=5)
    a4 = a4.mean()
    print('Cross-val mean: ', a4)
    mean_acc = round(((a1 + a2 + a3 + a4)/4) * 100, 2)
    logreg_acc.append(mean_acc)
    print('logreg has a mean accuracy score of: ' + str(mean_acc) + '%\n')
    validationAccuracy.append(mean_acc)
    
    validation_acc.append(a2)
    training_acc.append(a1)
    mse_valid.append(mean_squared_error(y_test, Y_pred))
    mse_train.append(mean_squared_error(y_train, logreg.predict(X_train)))
    
    # actual
    logreg.fit(X, y)
    cols = list(test_data_log.columns.values)
    for col in cols:
        test_data_log[col].fillna(test_data_log[col].mean(), inplace=True)
    Y_pred = logreg.predict(test_data_log)
    Y_pred_logreg.append(Y_pred)
    
logreg_acc_max = max(logreg_acc)

for i in range (len(logreg_acc)):
    if logreg_acc[i] == logreg_acc_max :
        logreg_acc_max_index = i
       
print('The best accuracy score was: ' + str(logreg_acc_max))

6.2 Support Vector Machines: ¶

In general, this algorithm is thought of as having higher accuracy over other classification algorithms and appears to perform well with higher dimensional datasets. This method creates hyper-planes to seperated data classes and constructs multiple, until it finds the best line of fit. When a single plane is unable to seperate the data, the algorithm transforms the data into a seperable form. This is not limited to linear transformations which increases the performance of the algorithm over others. Learn more

6.3 K-nearest neighbours (kNN): ¶

This algorithm is a non-linear prediction model which means it is no limited to hyperplaning to seperate data. KNN can be used as both a classification or regression model, making it exteremely versatile. One downside of this model is that due to its complexity, large datasets are required to improve the accuracy, but it works efficiently on such large datastes. This model works at prediction rather than fitted, by which it selects values from the training set nearest (by obtaining Euclidian distance) to the new value and uses these to predict the outcome. The nearest neighbours are averaged or voted on (obtaine the mode: most commonly occuring value), depending on the problem type at hand. Learn more

6.4 Gaussian naive bayes: ¶

6.5 Perceptron: ¶

This method is inspired by the functionality of a neuron and acts by forming a hyperplane between data for classification, thus acting in a similar way to a linear regression model. It is possible to create a layer of these "neurons" to handle data effectively. The unit step function is made use of to predict the outcome. A disadvantage is that it is confined to linear solutions. Learn more

6.7 Stochastic gradient descent: ¶

In a classification specific problem, this method minimizes cross-entropy functions, however, this depends on the required predictions to be made. The goal is to minimize the prediction error by adjustion the model parameters to find the best fit. Learn more

6.8 Decision Tree: ¶

A decision tree is a flow-chart like structure that depends on the features present in the dataset. A decison tree is based on the features in a datset and follow several path to ultimately reach the target variable. In this case the target variable is to determine if a passenger died or not. Decision trees can either be a classification or regression tree. In this problem we want to classify if a passenger died or not. In developing a tree we decide which features to include and exclude in order to split and move along a branch of the tree. [Learn more here] (https://towardsdatascience.com/decision-trees-in-machine-learning-641b9c4e8052)

In [121]:
decision_tree_acc = []
Y_pred_decision_tree = []
validation_acc = []
training_acc = []
mse_valid = []
mse_train = []

for i in range(len(featureEngineering)):
    if type(featureEngineering[i]) != np.ndarray:
        feature = featureEngineering[i].copy(deep=True) 
        X = feature.drop(columns= ['Survived'])
        y = feature['Survived']
    test_data = testFeatureEngineering[i].copy(deep=True) 
    
    # validation
    X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test=train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.2,random_state=1)
    decision_tree = DecisionTreeClassifier()
    decision_tree.fit(X_train, y_train)
    Y_pred = decision_tree.predict(X_test)
    
    # accuracy
    print('Accuracy for fe' + str(i))
    a1 = metrics.accuracy_score(y_train, decision_tree.predict(X_train))
    print("Train set Accuracy: ", a1)
    a2 = metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, Y_pred)
    print("Test set Accuracy: ", a2)
    a3 = f1_score(y_test, Y_pred, average='weighted')
    print('F1 Score:', a3)
    a4 = cross_val_score(decision_tree,X_train,y_train,cv=5)
    a4 = a4.mean()
    print('Cross-val mean: ', a4)
    mean_acc = round(((a1 + a2 + a3 + a4)/4) * 100, 2)
    decision_tree_acc.append(mean_acc)
    print('decision_tree has a mean accuracy score of: ' + str(mean_acc) + '%\n')
    validationAccuracy.append(mean_acc)
    
    validation_acc.append(a2)
    training_acc.append(a1)
    mse_valid.append(mean_squared_error(y_test, Y_pred))
    mse_train.append(mean_squared_error(y_train, decision_tree.predict(X_train)))
    
    # actual
    decision_tree.fit(X, y)
    cols = list(test_data.columns.values)
    for col in cols:

6.9 Random Forest: ¶

Random Forest classifiers consist of a decision tree. A decision tree can either be a classification or regression tree. Our decision variable is categorical and therefore the classfier is applied to the data. The random forest model consist of several decsion trees that build on each other and is related to bootstrap samples. Bootstrap samples refers to smaller samples that are drwan from the original data. Learn more here and here(https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/computer-science/random-forest-classifier)

7.3 Model Ensembling¶

(a) The Voting Classifier Ensembler¶

The Voting Classifier is used to combine the conceptually different machine learning classifiers and use the average predicted probabilities (soft vote) to predict the class labels. Such a classifier can be useful for a set of equally well performing model in order to balance out their individual weaknesses. From the tuned model analysis in the section above we deduce that Feature Engineering 12 works best for our 2 chosen models. The two models which have been chosen are the logistic Regression and Random Forest models. This method results in our Best Prediction with a public score of 0.775.

The classifiers have been well calibrating in the Model Tuning section, thus the soft voting method has been implemented as:

$$\hat{y} = \arg \max_i \sum^{m}{j=1} wj p{ij},$$

where wj is the weight that can be assigned to the jth classifier.

In [135]:
voting_clf_soft = VotingClassifier(estimators = [('lr',best_clf_lr_list[1]),('rf',best_clf_rf_list[1])], voting = 'soft')

y_hat_vc_soft =  voting_clf_soft.predict(dataFrame_test).astype(int)

b) Ensembling using the Bagging Classifier for Feature Engineering 12.

Bagging is a generic ensemble approach. It works by applying comparable classifiers to tiny sections of the dataset and then taking the average of all predictions. The variance is reduced as a result of averaging. Unlike Voting Classifier, Bagging employs comparable classifiers.

In [136]:

Ensembling using Boost

Boosting is an ensembling method that employs successive classifier learning. It is a gradual improvement of a flawed model. Boosting functions as follows:

First, a model is trained on the entire dataset. Now the model will correctly identify some occurrences while incorrectly identifying others. In the following iteration, the learner will pay greater attention to the incorrectly anticipated instances or assign them more weight. As a result, it will attempt to accurately forecast the incorrect occurrence. This iterative process is now ongoing, and additional classifiers are added to the model until the accuracy limit is attained. XGBoost is designed to improve large-scale boosted tree algorithms.
